For the second year, photojournalist Michael Bryant shot hundreds of photos for the second installment of the #BlackHistoryUntold project. Here are a few outtakes that didn't make it to print or online. 

In his words: "The object of these portraits is to get at the joy that each of these subjects felt at a certain point in their lives as African-Americans. Instead of me telling the subjects how I want them to pose or look at the camera, I start by telling them, "We are going to have a conversation." Then I begin talking to them about their lives and how the important moments of their lives have shaped who they are. When this happens all of the subjects open up and let me see, for a few moments, the happiness that dwells inside them.

It has been a privilege for me to spend time with these special people and my joy is they trusted me enough to open themselves up to me." - Michael Bryant

Read all the essays at: www.philly.com/blackhistory2017.

status_message:
Slime is cool again! And you can make it at home (perhaps a perfect snow day activity?). Here's how:

Measure 1 tablespoon of glue (such as Elmer's) into a cup. Add 2 teaspoons of water and stir well. Add 2 teaspoons of borax solution (that's 1 tablespoon of borax dissolved in a cup of warm water) and stir the mixture.

Your slime will be sticky for about a minute. Pull it out of the cup and knead it with your fingers until it feels drier and less sticky. Store it in a sealed bag in the refrigerator.
link_name: How to Make Your Own Slime
